      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are looking a bit weird. the leaves on the bottom are turning kind of yellow, but the top ones look okay for now. any idea what's going on? also how do i fix the soil if it's a pH issue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The yellowing of your lower leaves is a classic sign of nutrient deficiency, often caused by the plant moving nutrients from older growth to support new top growth, or potentially due to root issues like overwatering or lack of oxygen. To fix the soil pH, you can add lime to raise it or sulfur to lower it, but first, you should test the soil to see if a pH imbalance is the actual culprit rather than a simple nutrient deficit. If your soil is too acidic, mixing in garden lime will help neutralize it, while too much acidity can be corrected with elemental sulfur or iron supplements. Since you have a small number of plants, it might be worth checking if they are being overwatered, as wet soil can suffocate roots and mimic pH problems. If the issue persists despite these adjustments, you may need to replace the soil entirely with a fresh, well-draining mix.",
