    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i dont think i'm overwatering though. i've been pretty careful with the schedule. i just feel like the nutrients are disappearing way too fast, almost like something is actively stripping them away from the older leaves. is there anything else that causes that kind of rapid depletion?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That \"active stripping\" feeling is almost certainly your tomato plants' natural defense mechanism, not an external thief, but it can feel like a rapid depletion if the soil is too nutrient-poor to begin with. When the bottom leaves turn yellow, the plant is essentially cannibalizing the older foliage to feed the new growth at the top, a process that happens faster if the soil lacks sufficient nitrogen or phosphorus to sustain the crop. To stop this cycle, you need to replenish the soil with a balanced fertilizer that mimics natural compost, perhaps adding a little crushed eggshells for calcium to strengthen the leaves against this stress. If the yellowing spreads quickly to the upper leaves or the plants look wilting despite watering, it could indicate a root rot issue where the soil is too compacted, preventing the roots from absorbing what little nutrients remain. In that case, loosening the soil around the base of the plants and applying a top-dressing of compost might help the roots recover and stop the \"stripping\" behavior.",
      "source": "target",
